def _get_time_bins(self, ax):
        if not isinstance(ax, DatetimeIndex):
            raise TypeError(
                "axis must be a DatetimeIndex, but got "
                f"an instance of {type(ax).__name__}"
            )
    
        if len(ax) == 0:
            binner = labels = DatetimeIndex(data=[], freq=self.freq, name=ax.name, tz=ax.tz)
            return binner, [], labels
    
        first, last = _get_timestamp_range_edges(
            ax.min(), ax.max(), self.freq, closed=self.closed, base=self.base
        )

        # GH #12037
        # start and end both directly instead of calling replace() on them
        # because replace() will impact the nanosecond part
        # so last bin may be slightly before the end if the end contains
        # nanosecond part and lead to `Values falls after last bin` error
        binner = labels = date_range(
            start=first,
            end=last,
            periods=len(ax),  # Equivalent to freq=self.freq
            tz=ax.tz,
            name=ax.name,
            ambiguous="infer"
        )

        ax_values = ax.asi8
        # Since applying `tz_convert` to the timedelta values will impact the nanosecond part,
        # we don't need to adjust the time zones of the bin edges and labels.
        bin_edges = self._adjust_bin_edges(ax_values)
        labels = binner

        # general version, knowing nothing about relative frequencies
        bins = lib.generate_bins_dt64(
            ax_values, bin_edges, self.closed
        )
    
        if self.closed == "right" and self.label == "right":
            labels = labels[1:]

        if ax.hasnans:
            binner = binner.insert(0, NaT)
            labels = labels.insert(0, NaT)

       # if we end up with more labels than bins
        # adjust the labels
        # GH4076
        if len(bins) < len(labels):
            labels = labels[: len(bins)]
    
        return binner, bins, labels
